data.content:
## What happened

**C# 14 span overload resolution change.** The compiler now prefers `MemoryExtensions.Contains(Span<T>, T)` over `Enumerable.Contains(IEnumerable<T>, T)` when called on an array. Expression trees cannot represent `Span<T>`-based methods, so the compiled expression throws at runtime.

## Fix

Cast the array to `IEnumerable<int>` so the compiler binds to `Enumerable.Contains`:

```csharp
// Option 1: Cast in the expression
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);

// Option 2: Use .AsEnumerable()
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => array.AsEnumerable().Contains(num);

// Option 3: Call Enumerable.Contains explicitly
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);
```

This same issue affects `Enumerable.Reverse` on arrays (now resolves to the in-place `Span` version). The pattern is the same: disambiguate with `.AsEnumerable()` or a static call.
